<h1>LG Washer Shaking & Loud — Fix It Same Day</h1>

<p>An LG washer that shakes, walks across the floor, or bangs loudly on spin is usually telling you the drum can't stay balanced. Most of the time it's a load issue or a machine that isn't level — but a loud, persistent rumble points to worn suspension or a failing drum bearing. Here's how to steady it yourself and when it needs parts. Same-day across LA, Orange County and Ventura. Call (323) 990-7550.</p>

<h2>Why Your LG Washer Shakes or Bangs</h2>
<p>On the spin cycle the drum ramps up to high speed to wring water out of the laundry, and anything that lets it move around at that speed turns into shaking and noise. An off-balance load, an unlevel base, or worn suspension all let the drum swing instead of staying centered, and the machine fights to slow it back down. When the imbalance is the cause, you'll often see a <a href="/washer/error-codes/lg-washer-ue-error/">UE code</a> on the panel as the washer tries to redistribute the load.</p>

<h2>What Causes the Shaking</h2>
<p>In order of how often we find it on a service call:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Unbalanced load</strong> — one heavy item like a comforter or bath mat spinning on its own is the most common cause.</li>
  <li><strong>Not level, or feet not locked</strong>, so the machine rocks and walks.</li>
  <li><strong>Shipping bolts left in</strong> on a recently delivered machine — this causes severe shaking.</li>
  <li><strong>Worn shock absorbers or suspension rods</strong> that no longer dampen the drum.</li>
  <li><strong>Worn drum bearing</strong> — a loud rumble or grind on spin, usually on higher-mileage machines.</li>
  <li><strong>Loose counterweight</strong> that's no longer steadying the drum.</li>
</ul>

<h2>What You Can Safely Check Yourself</h2>
<p>Start with the load: spread it evenly around the drum and don't spin a single heavy item by itself — add a couple of towels to balance it out. Next, check the washer is sitting level and isn't rocking; adjust and lock the leveling feet if it does. If the machine was recently delivered, look at the back and confirm the shipping bolts were removed — leaving them in is a frequent cause of violent shaking on a new install. Finally, make sure the cabinet isn't touching a wall or nearby cabinets, which amplifies the noise.</p>

<h2>When It's the Suspension or Bearing</h2>
<p>If the load is balanced and the machine is level but it still shakes hard or rumbles, the cause is usually worn shock absorbers or suspension rods, and on higher-mileage machines a worn drum bearing. Our techs check the drum for play and listen for the bearing under spin before quoting. Shock absorbers or suspension run $280–360 installed; a worn drum bearing runs $320–420. The $65 diagnostic is waived when we do the repair.</p>

<h2>Normal Vibration vs a Real Problem</h2>
<p>Some movement is normal — every washer vibrates a little as it ramps up to spin speed, and a faint hum is nothing to worry about. What isn't normal is a machine that walks across the floor, bangs hard enough to rattle the room, or makes a deep metallic grind. If steadying the load and leveling it doesn't quiet it down, that's the line between normal and a repair, and it's worth getting checked before it wears other parts.</p>

<p>Washer banging or walking across the floor? Our LG Dryer Repair techs run same-day washer vibration repairs across LA, Orange County, and Ventura County — most load and leveling issues are sorted on the spot, and worn shocks or a bearing are a same-visit fix. Call (323) 990-7550; the $65 diagnostic is waived when you approve the repair.</p>

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions — LG Washer Shaking</h2>

<h3>Why is my LG washer shaking so much?</h3>
<p>Your LG washer shakes when the drum can't stay balanced on spin — usually an off-balance load or a machine that isn't level, sometimes worn suspension. A loud grinding rumble points instead to a failing drum bearing.</p>

<h3>Can I fix an LG washer that's shaking myself?</h3>
<p>Usually, yes. Spread the load out evenly and avoid spinning one heavy item alone, then check the washer is level and the feet are locked so it doesn't rock. If it was recently delivered, make sure the shipping bolts were removed from the back — leaving them in causes severe shaking. If it still shakes when balanced and level, the suspension or bearing needs a tech.</p>

<h3>How much does it cost to fix an LG washer that shakes?</h3>
<p>If it's a load or leveling fix, it costs nothing beyond the $65 diagnostic, which is waived if a repair is needed. Worn shock absorbers or suspension rods run $280–360, and a worn drum bearing runs $320–420. We check the drum's play before quoting. We're licensed with the Bureau of Household Goods and Services (#49573).</p>

<h3>Why does my LG washer bang loudly only during the spin cycle?</h3>
<p>Spin is when the drum hits high speed, so any imbalance or worn part shows up exactly then — an off-center load, worn shocks that let the drum swing, or a loose counterweight all bang on spin. A deep metallic grind during spin usually means the drum bearing is worn and needs replacing.</p>

<h3>Is it bad to keep using an LG washer that shakes?</h3>
<p>It depends — light vibration is fine, but a washer that walks, bangs hard, or grinds can damage the suspension, the bearing, and even nearby cabinets over time. Balance the load and level it first; if the shaking or noise continues, get it checked before it does more damage.</p>

